This paper is about Estimation-of-Distribution Algorithms (EDAs), which are a type of randomized search heuristics used for optimization problems. The paper discusses the development of a new EDA called significance-based compact genetic algorithm (sig-cGA) and compares it with other EDAs. The paper also proves the time complexity of the sig-cGA algorithm for optimizing benchmark functions. Based on this information, the most likely arXiv CS sub-categories for this paper are cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), as the paper deals with optimization algorithms and their performance. The paper also involves statistical analysis and machine learning, which makes cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.LG (Machine Learning) likely sub-categories as well. Finally, the paper discusses the performance of different algorithms, which could make cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) a possible sub-category.
